> Can you explain the background of the change. It looks like to me that we are adding entries whenever someone poll an nonexistent table or key. Is this okay? Shouldn't failure be the default option here?

Updated the PR description with more details. We are sending sync responses only to keep the RPC available and to let the client know that there is no data available but we will send data when it becomes available. Failure and closing RCP connection (current behavior) does not conform to official gnmi spec

> @anders-nexthop https://github.com/sonic-net/sonic-gnmi/blob/master/sonic_data_client/mixed_db_client.go#L1454-L1463 For now, we use special syntax for a full configuration update. When we switch to using config replace, we should also change the syntax to replace "/".

I don't quite follow. I thought a full config update was represented with both and empty 'delete' path and an empty 'update' path. Is that not correct? What would we do differently to represent a config replace? If we can represent this operation in a different way we can leave the existing implementation in place, which may be desirable for compatibility. Are you perhaps suggesting that we could instead use the 'replace' path, passing in an empty path with the file contents as a value? For example:
```
    # from sonic-mgmt/tests/gnmi/test_gnmi_configdb.py
    delete_list = ["/sonic-db:CONFIG_DB/localhost/"]
    update_list = ["/sonic-db:CONFIG_DB/localhost/:@/root/%s" % filename]
    replace_list = ["/sonic-db:CONFIG_DB/localhost/:@/root/%s" % filename]

    gnmi_set(duthost, ptfhost, delete_list, update_list, [])                                       # this is the existing syntax

    gnmi_set(duthost, ptfhost, [], [], replace_list)                                                     # this would trigger ConfigReplace
```

@anders-nexthop 
yes, you are correct, we could instead use the 'replace' path, passing in an empty path with the file contents as a value

> @anders-nexthop yes, you are correct, we could instead use the 'replace' path, passing in an empty path with the file contents as a value

Yes that makes sense. I will make that change and update the PR.
yes, this operation should be persistent
